# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: blockchain-consensus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] A **Byzantine fault** is a condition of a system, particularly a distributed computing system, where a fault occurs such that different symptoms are presented to different observers, including imperfect information on whether a system component has failed.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is also known as a **Byzantine generals problem**, a **Byzantine agreement problem**, or a **Byzantine failure**.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine fault is any fault presenting different symptoms to different observers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] A Byzantine failure is the loss of a system service due to a Byzantine fault in systems that require consensus among multiple components.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The Byzantine allegory considers a number of generals who are attacking a fortress.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The generals must decide as a group whether to attack or retreat; some may prefer to attack, while others prefer to retreat.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The important thing is that all generals agree on a common decision, for a half-hearted attack by a few generals would become a rout, and would be worse than either a coordinated attack or a coordinated retreat.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated by the presence of treacherous generals who may not only cast a vote for a suboptimal strategy; they may do so selectively.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For instance, if nine generals are voting, four of whom support attacking while four others are in favor of retreat, the ninth general may send a vote of retreat to those generals in favor of retreat, and a vote of attack to the rest.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Those who received a retreat vote from the ninth general will retreat, while the rest will attack (which may not go well for the attackers).
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The problem is complicated further by the generals being physically separated and having to send their votes via messengers who may fail to deliver votes or may forge false votes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Without message signing, Byzantine fault tolerance can only be achieved if the total number of generals is greater than three times the number of disloyal (faulty) generals.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] There can be a default vote value given to missing messages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For example, missing messages can be given a "null" value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Further, if the agreement is that the null votes are in the majority, a pre-assigned default strategy can be used (e.g., retreat).
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The typical mapping of this allegory onto computer systems is that the computers are the generals and their digital communication system links are the messengers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Although the problem is formulated in the allegory as a decision-making and security problem, in electronics, it cannot be solved by cryptographic digital signatures alone, because failures such as incorrect voltages can propagate through the encryption process.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Thus, a faulty message could be sent such that some recipients detect the message as faulty (bad signature), others see it is having a good signature, and a third group also sees a good signature but with different message contents than the second group.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The problem of obtaining Byzantine consensus was conceived and formalized by Robert Shostak, who dubbed it the *interactive consistency* problem.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] This work was done in 1978 in the context of the NASA-sponsored SIFT project in the Computer Science Lab at SRI International.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] SIFT (for Software Implemented Fault Tolerance) was the brainchild of John Wensley, and was based on the idea of using multiple general-purpose computers that would communicate through pairwise messaging in order to reach a consensus, even if some of the computers were faulty.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] At the beginning of the project, it was not clear how many computers in total were needed to guarantee that a conspiracy of *n* faulty computers could not "thwart" the efforts of the correctly-operating ones to reach consensus.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Shostak showed that a minimum of 3*n+*1 are needed, and devised a two-round 3*n+1* messaging protocol that would work for *n*=1.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] His colleague Marshall Pease generalized the algorithm for any n > 0, proving that 3*n*+1 is both necessary and sufficient.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] These results, together with a later proof by Leslie Lamport of the sufficiency of 3*n* using digital signatures, were published in the seminal paper, *Reaching Agreement in the Presence of Faults.* The authors were awarded the 2005 Edsger W.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] To make the interactive consistency problem easier to understand, Lamport devised a colorful allegory in which a group of army generals formulate a plan for attacking a city.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] In its original version, the story cast the generals as commanders of the Albanian army.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The name was changed, eventually settling on "Byzantine", at the suggestion of Jack Goldberg to future-proof any potential offense-giving.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] This formulation of the problem, together with some additional results, were presented by the same authors in their 1982 paper, "The Byzantine Generals Problem".
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The objective of Byzantine fault tolerance is to be able to defend against failures of system components with or without symptoms that prevent other components of the system from reaching an agreement among themselves, where such an agreement is needed for the correct operation of the system.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The remaining operationally correct components of a Byzantine fault tolerant system will be able to continue providing the system's service as originally intended, assuming there are a sufficient number of accurately-operating components to maintain the service.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] When considering failure propagation only via errors, Byzantine failures are considered the most general and most difficult class of failures among the failure modes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The so-called fail-stop failure mode occupies the simplest end of the spectrum.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Thus, Byzantine failures can confuse failure detection systems, which makes fault tolerance difficult.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Despite the allegory, a Byzantine failure is not necessarily a security problem involving hostile human interference: it can arise purely from physical or software faults.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] This kind of fault tolerance does not encompass the correctness of the value itself; for example, an adversarial component that deliberately sends an incorrect value, but sends that same value consistently to all components, will not be caught in the Byzantine fault tolerance scheme.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Several early solutions were described by Lamport, Shostak, and Pease in 1982.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] There are many systems that claim BFT without meeting the above minimum requirements (e.g., blockchain).
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Given that there is mathematical proof that this is impossible, these claims need to include a caveat that their definition of BFT strays from the original.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] That is, systems such as blockchain don't guarantee agreement.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] They use resource-intensive mechanisms that make disagreements impractical to maintain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Several system architectures were designed c.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] 1980 that implemented Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] These include: Draper's FTMP, Honeywell's MMFCS, and SRI's SIFT.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] In 1999, Miguel Castro and Barbara Liskov introduced the "Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance" (PBFT) algorithm, which provides high-performance Byzantine state machine replication, processing thousands of requests per second with sub-millisecond increases in latency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] After PBFT, several BFT protocols were introduced to improve its robustness and performance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For instance, Q/U, HQ, Zyzzyva, and ABsTRACTs, addressed the performance and cost issues; whereas other protocols, like Aardvark and RBFT, addressed its robustness issues.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, Adapt tried to make use of existing BFT protocols, through switching between them in an adaptive way, to improve system robustness and performance as the underlying conditions change.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Furthermore, BFT protocols were introduced that leverage trusted components to reduce the number of replicas, e.g., A2M-PBFT-EA and MinBFT.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Recent research addresses the scalability limits of traditional BFT implementations (which often incur $O(n^{2})$ communication complexity) by parallelizing consensus.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For example, the Cerberus protocol maps data to a large, fixed state space to couple consensus instances with specific transaction sets.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] This allows BFT processes to run independently in parallel, enabling linear scalability relative to the network size.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Several examples of Byzantine failures that have occurred are given in two equivalent journal papers.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] These and other examples are described on the NASA DASHlink web pages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance mechanisms use components that repeat an incoming message (or just its signature, which can be reduced to just a single bit of information if self-checking pairs are used for nodes) to other recipients of that incoming message.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] All these mechanisms make the assumption that the act of repeating a message blocks the propagation of Byzantine symptoms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For systems that have a high degree of safety or security criticality, these assumptions must be proven to be true to an acceptable level of fault coverage.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] When providing proof through testing, one difficulty is creating a sufficiently wide range of signals with Byzantine symptoms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Such testing will likely require specialized fault injectors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Byzantine errors were observed infrequently and at irregular points during endurance testing for the newly constructed *Virginia*-class submarine, at least through 2005 (when the issues were publicly reported).
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The Bitcoin network works in parallel to generate a blockchain with proof of work allowing the system to overcome Byzantine failures and reach a coherent global view of the system's state.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Some proof of stake blockchains also use BFT algorithms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Byzantine fault tolerance is a crucial concept in blockchain technology, ensuring that a network can continue to function even when some nodes (participants) fail or act maliciously.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] This tolerance is necessary because blockchains are decentralized systems with no central authority, making it essential to achieve consensus among nodes, even if some try to disrupt the process.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Ensuring that an AI system behaves reliably and as intended, especially in the presence of unexpected faults or adversarial conditions, is a complex challenge.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] By accepting that components may fail, and further that frontier AI models may deceive, Byzantine fault tolerance has been proposed as an approach towards AI safety.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Structuring AI systems as ensembles of AI artifacts or modules that check and balance each other leads to strong assurances that no single errant or deceptive component can easily steer the system into an unsafe state.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] , BFT-based systems are designed to tolerate up to one-third of faulty or malicious nodes without compromising the network's integrity.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] Instead of relying on a central authority, the network's security depends on the ability of honest nodes to outnumber and outmaneuver malicious ones.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] BFT is especially important in private or permissioned blockchains, where a limited number of known participants need to reach a consensus quickly and securely.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] These networks often use BFT protocols to enhance performance and security.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] For example, SAFEbus can achieve Byzantine fault tolerance within the order of a microsecond of added latency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The SpaceX Dragon considers Byzantine fault tolerance in its design.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The Ares rocket avionics, now the Space Launch System (SLS), utilizes a triplex with an interstage of accomplish Byzantine resilience.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] The Orion spacecraft utilizes self-checking pairs to detect and mask Byzantine faults.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] In legislatures, civil societies, polls, statistical surveys, and so forth, systems that require a minimum supermajority threshold agreement greater than two-thirds are similar to consensus reflective of Byzantine Fault Tolerant -like characteristics.
[src:blockchain-consensus/byzantine-fault] By contrast, systems that operate on the sub-supermajority basis of simple majorities or a minority government could be vulnerable to Byzantine fault -like behavior.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A fundamental problem in distributed computing and multi-agent systems is to achieve overall system reliability in the presence of a number of faulty processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] This often requires coordinating processes to reach **consensus**, or agree on some data value that is needed during computation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Example applications of consensus include agreeing on what transactions to commit to a database in which order, state machine replication, and atomic broadcasts.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Real-world applications often requiring consensus include cloud computing, clock synchronization, PageRank, opinion formation, smart power grids, state estimation, control of UAVs (and multiple robots/agents in general), load balancing, blockchain, and others.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem requires agreement among a number of processes (or agents) on a single data value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Some of the processes (agents) may fail or be unreliable in other ways, so consensus protocols must be fault-tolerant or resilient.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The processes must put forth their candidate values, communicate with one another, and agree on a single consensus value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem is a fundamental problem in controlling multi-agent systems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] One approach to generating consensus is for all processes (agents) to agree on a majority value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In this context, a majority requires at least one more than half of the available votes (where each process is given a vote).
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] However, one or more faulty processes may skew the resultant outcome such that consensus may not be reached or may be reached incorrectly.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Protocols that solve consensus problems are designed to deal with a limited number of faulty processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] These protocols must satisfy several requirements to be useful.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For instance, a trivial protocol could have all processes output binary value 1.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] This is not useful; thus, the requirement is modified such that the production must depend on the input.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] That is, the output value of a consensus protocol must be the input value of some process.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Another requirement is that a process may decide upon an output value only once, and this decision is irrevocable.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A method is correct in an execution if it does not experience a failure.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A consensus protocol tolerating halting failures must satisfy the following properties.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Eventually, every correct process decides some value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Every correct process must agree on the same value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Variations on the definition of *integrity* may be appropriate, according to the application.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For example, a weaker type of integrity would be for the decision value to equal a value that some correct process proposed – not necessarily all of them.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] There is also a condition known as **validity** in the literature which refers to the property that a message sent by a process must be delivered.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A protocol that can correctly guarantee consensus amongst n processes of which at most t fail is said to be *t-resilient*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In evaluating the performance of consensus protocols two factors of interest are *running time* and *message complexity*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Running time is given in Big O notation in the number of rounds of message exchange as a function of some input parameters (typically the number of processes and/or the size of the input domain).
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Message complexity refers to the amount of message traffic that is generated by the protocol.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Other factors may include memory usage and the size of messages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Varying models of computation may define a "consensus problem".
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Some models may deal with fully connected graphs, while others may deal with rings and trees.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In some models message authentication is allowed, whereas in others processes are completely anonymous.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Shared memory models in which processes communicate by accessing objects in shared memory are also an important area of research.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In most models of communication protocol participants communicate through *authenticated channels.* This means that messages are not anonymous, and receivers know the source of every message they receive.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Some models assume a stronger, *transferable* form of authentication, where each *message* is signed by the sender, so that a receiver knows not just the immediate source of every message, but the participant that initially created the message.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] This stronger type of authentication is achieved by digital signatures, and when this stronger form of authentication is available, protocols can tolerate a larger number of faults.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The two different authentication models are often called *oral communication* and *written communication* models.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In an oral communication model, the immediate source of information is known, whereas in stronger, written communication models, every step along the receiver learns not just the immediate source of the message, but the communication history of the message.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the most traditional **single-value** consensus protocols such as Paxos, cooperating nodes agree on a single value such as an integer, which may be of variable size so as to encode useful metadata such as a transaction committed to a database.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A special case of the single-value consensus problem, called **binary consensus**, restricts the input, and hence the output domain, to a single binary digit {0,1}.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] While not highly useful by themselves, binary consensus protocols are often useful as building blocks in more general consensus protocols, especially for asynchronous consensus.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In **multi-valued** consensus protocols such as Multi-Paxos and Raft, the goal is to agree on not just a single value but a series of values over time, forming a progressively-growing history.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] While multi-valued consensus may be achieved naively by running multiple iterations of a single-valued consensus protocol in succession, many optimizations and other considerations such as reconfiguration support can make multi-valued consensus protocols more efficient in practice.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] There are two types of failures a process may undergo, a crash failure or a Byzantine failure.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A *crash failure* occurs when a process abruptly stops and does not resume.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] *Byzantine failure*s are failures in which absolutely no conditions are imposed.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For example, they may occur as a result of the malicious actions of an adversary.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A process that experiences a Byzantine failure may send contradictory or conflicting data to other processes, or it may sleep and then resume activity after a lengthy delay.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Of the two types of failures, Byzantine failures are far more disruptive.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Thus, a consensus protocol tolerating Byzantine failures must be resilient to every possible error that can occur.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] must have been proposed by some correct process.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The consensus problem may be considered in the case of asynchronous or synchronous systems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] While real world communications are often inherently asynchronous, it is more practical and often easier to model synchronous systems, given that asynchronous systems naturally involve more issues than synchronous ones.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In synchronous systems, it is assumed that all communications proceed in *rounds*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In one round, a process may send all the messages it requires, while receiving all messages from other processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In this manner, no message from one round may influence any messages sent within the same round.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous message-passing distributed system, in which at least one process may have a *crash failure*, it has been proven in the famous 1985 **FLP impossibility result** by Fischer, Lynch and Paterson that a deterministic algorithm for achieving consensus is impossible.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] This impossibility result derives from worst-case scheduling scenarios, which are unlikely to occur in practice except in adversarial situations such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In most normal situations, process scheduling has a degree of natural randomness.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In an asynchronous model, some forms of failures can be handled by a synchronous consensus protocol.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For instance, the loss of a communication link may be modeled as a process which has suffered a Byzantine failure.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Randomized consensus algorithms can circumvent the FLP impossibility result by achieving both safety and liveness with overwhelming probability, even under worst-case scheduling scenarios such as an intelligent denial-of-service attacker in the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Consensus algorithms traditionally assume that the set of participating nodes is fixed and given at the outset: that is, that some prior (manual or automatic) configuration process has **permissioned** a particular known group of participants who can authenticate each other as members of the group.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the absence of such a well-defined, closed group with authenticated members, a Sybil attack against an open consensus group can defeat even a Byzantine consensus algorithm, simply by creating enough virtual participants to overwhelm the fault tolerance threshold.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A **permissionless** consensus protocol, in contrast, allows anyone in the network to join dynamically and participate without prior permission, but instead imposes a different form of artificial cost or barrier to entry to mitigate the Sybil attack threat.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Motivated in part by the high energy cost of this approach, subsequent permissionless consensus protocols have proposed or adopted other alternative participation rules for Sybil attack protection, such as proof of stake, proof of space, and proof of authority.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Three agreement problems of interest are as follows.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A collection of n processes, numbered from 0 to $n-1,$ communicate by sending messages to one another.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] 2. for any two correct processes, each process receives the same value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] It is also known as The General's Problem.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For *n* processes in a partially synchronous system (the system alternates between good and bad periods of synchrony), each process chooses a private value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] 2. all messages sent in a round by a correct process are received in the same round by all correct processes (consistency property).
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] It can be shown that variations of these problems are equivalent in that the solution for a problem in one type of model may be the solution for another problem in another type of model.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For example, a solution to the Weak Byzantine General problem in a synchronous authenticated message passing model leads to a solution for Weak Interactive Consistency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] An interactive consistency algorithm can solve the consensus problem by having each process choose the majority value in its consensus vector as its consensus value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] There is a t-resilient anonymous synchronous protocol which solves the Byzantine Generals problem, if ${\tfrac {t}{n}}<{\tfrac {1}{3}}$ and the Weak Byzantine Generals case where t is the number of failures and n is the number of processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] For systems with n processors, of which f are Byzantine, it has been shown that there exists no algorithm that solves the consensus problem for $n\leq 3f$ in the *oral-messages model*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The proof is constructed by first showing the impossibility for the three-node case $n=3$ and using this result to argue about partitions of processors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the *written-messages model* there are protocols that can tolerate $n=f+1$ .
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In a fully asynchronous system there is no consensus solution that can tolerate one or more crash failures even when only requiring the non triviality property.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] This result is sometimes called the FLP impossibility proof named after the authors Michael J.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Fischer, Nancy Lynch, and Mike Paterson who were awarded a Dijkstra Prize for this significant work.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The FLP result has been mechanically verified to hold even under fairness assumptions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] However, FLP does not state that consensus can never be reached: merely that under the model's assumptions, no algorithm can always reach consensus in bounded time.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In practice it is highly unlikely to occur.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The Paxos consensus algorithm by Leslie Lamport, and variants of it such as Raft, are used pervasively in widely deployed distributed and cloud computing systems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] These algorithms are typically synchronous, dependent on an elected leader to make progress, and tolerate only crashes and not Byzantine failures.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Other protocols, such as Cerberus, have been developed to apply Byzantine fault-tolerant consensus to sharded distributed ledgers and have been the subject of academic analysis.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] An example of a polynomial time binary consensus protocol that tolerates Byzantine failures is the Phase King algorithm by Garay and Berman.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The algorithm solves consensus in a synchronous message passing model with *n* processes and up to *f* failures, provided *n* > 4*f*.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the phase king algorithm, there are *f* + 1 phases, with 2 rounds per phase.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Each process keeps track of its preferred output (initially equal to the process's own input value).
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the first round of each phase each process broadcasts its own preferred value to all other processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] It then receives the values from all processes and determines which value is the majority value and its count.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In the second round of the phase, the process whose id matches the current phase number is designated the king of the phase.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The king broadcasts the majority value it observed in the first round and serves as a tie breaker.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Each process then updates its preferred value as follows.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] If the count of the majority value the process observed in the first round is greater than *n*/2 + *f*, the process changes its preference to that majority value; otherwise it uses the phase king's value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] At the end of *f* + 1 phases the processes output their preferred values.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Google has implemented a distributed lock service library called Chubby.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Chubby maintains lock information in small files which are stored in a replicated database to achieve high availability in the face of failures.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The database is implemented on top of a fault-tolerant log layer which is based on the Paxos consensus algorithm.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] In this scheme, Chubby clients communicate with the Paxos *master* in order to access/update the replicated log; i.e., read/write to the files.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Many peer-to-peer online real-time strategy games use a modified lockstep protocol as a consensus protocol in order to manage game state between players in a game.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Each game action results in a game state delta broadcast to all other players in the game along with a hash of the total game state.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Each player validates the change by applying the delta to their own game state and comparing the game state hashes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Another well-known approach is called MSR-type algorithms which have been used widely in fields from computer science to control theory.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Bitcoin uses proof of work, a difficulty adjustment function and a reorganization function to achieve permissionless consensus in its open peer-to-peer network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] To extend bitcoin's blockchain or distributed ledger, *miners* attempt to solve a cryptographic puzzle, where probability of finding a solution is proportional to the computational effort expended in hashes per second.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The node that first solves such a puzzle has their proposed version of the next block of transactions added to the ledger and eventually accepted by all other nodes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] As any node in the network can attempt to solve the proof-of-work problem, a Sybil attack is infeasible in principle unless the attacker has over 50% of the computational resources of the network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Ethereum, NEO, STRATIS, ...) use proof of stake, in which nodes compete to append blocks and earn associated rewards in proportion to *stake*, or existing cryptocurrency allocated and locked or *staked* for some time period.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] One advantage of a 'proof of stake' over a 'proof of work' system, is the high energy consumption demanded by the latter.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] As an example, bitcoin mining (2018) is estimated to consume non-renewable energy sources at an amount similar to the entire nations of Czech Republic or Jordan, while the total energy consumption of Ethereum, the largest proof of stake network, is just under that of 205 average US households.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Some cryptocurrencies, such as Ripple, use a system of validating nodes to validate the ledger.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Step 4: the final round requires 80% agreement.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Other participation rules used in permissionless consensus protocols to impose barriers to entry and resist sybil attacks include proof of authority, proof of space, proof of burn, or proof of elapsed time.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Proposed approaches to achieving one-per-person distribution of consensus power for proof of personhood include physical pseudonym parties, social networks, pseudonymized government-issued identities, and biometrics.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] To solve the consensus problem in a shared-memory system, concurrent objects must be introduced.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] A concurrent object, or shared object, is a data structure which helps concurrent processes communicate to reach an agreement.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Traditional implementations using critical sections face the risk of crashing if some process dies inside the critical section or sleeps for an intolerably long time.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Researchers defined wait-freedom as the guarantee that the algorithm completes in a finite number of steps.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The **consensus number** of a concurrent object is defined to be the maximum number of processes in the system which can reach consensus by the given object in a wait-free implementation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Objects with a consensus number of n can implement any object with a consensus number of n or lower, but cannot implement any objects with a higher consensus number.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] The consensus numbers form what is called Herlihy's hierarchy of synchronization objects.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] According to the hierarchy, read/write registers cannot solve consensus even in a 2-process system.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] Data structures like stacks and queues can only solve consensus between two processes.
[src:blockchain-consensus/consensus-computer-science] However, some concurrent objects are universal (notated in the table with $\infty$ ), which means they can solve consensus among any number of processes and they can simulate any other objects through an operation sequence.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] Peercoin is based on an August 2012 paper that listed the authors as Scott Nadal and Sunny King.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] King, who also created Primecoin, is a pseudonym.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] The Peercoin source code is distributed under the MIT/X11 software license.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] Peercoin uses both the proof-of-work and proof-of-stake algorithms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] Both are used to spread the distribution of new coins.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] During its primary years, Peercoin relied heavily on PoW, although there has now been a transition to PoS.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] Proof-of-stake is used to secure the network: The chain with longest PoS coin age wins in case of a blockchain split-up.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] To target a global 1% annual inflation rate, individual stakes typically receive a 3 - 5% annual reward, as only a minority of coins are actively staked.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] This reward is based on a dynamic portion (75% of the reward) and a static portion (25% of the reward).
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] The dynamic portion of the reward for an individual stake is based on the number of coins, their unspent age, and degree of global staking participation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] Stake-for-Stake, periods of low (high) global staking participation will result in a higher (lower) dynamic reward.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] The static portion of the reward is based on the fraction of the existing total coin supply minted on average in a year, and is awarded regardless of stake size.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] As of December 2024, the static reward for a proof-of-stake block is approximately 1.4 PPC.
[src:blockchain-consensus/peercoin] A transaction fee prevents spam and is burned (instead of being collected by a miner), benefiting the overall network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] For a blockchain transaction to be recognized, it must be appended to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] In a proof-of-stake blockchain, the appending entities are named *minters* or **validators** (in proof-of-work blockchains, this task is carried out by the miners); in most protocols, the validators receive a reward for doing so.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] For the blockchain to remain secure, it must have a mechanism to prevent a malicious user or group from taking over a majority of validation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] PoS accomplishes this by requiring that validators have some quantity of blockchain tokens, requiring potential attackers to acquire a large fraction of the tokens on the blockchain to mount an attack.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Proof-of-work (PoW), another commonly used consensus mechanism, uses a validation of computational prowess to verify transactions, requiring a potential attacker to acquire a large fraction of the computational power of the validator network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] This incentivizes consuming huge quantities of energy.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Riposo and Gupta showed that a formal PoS mathematical model can derive a metric for the expected gain of a staker.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] They introduced a forward-method model that computes staking rewards as the staking return per block-validation period and proved that the resulting interest equals the ratio of the average staking gain to the total staked coins.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The model incorporates PoS-specific factors such as slashing (penalties for misbehavior) and Maximal Extractable Value (MEV), showing that slashing reduces expected rewards and that MEV links transaction-fee extraction to the average staking gain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] In addition, the authors illustrated the model using Ethereum 2.0, and presented an analogous derivation for PoW consensus.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Early PoS implementations were plagued by a number of new attacks that exploited the unique vulnerabilities of the PoS protocols.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Eventually, two dominant designs emerged: *Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based* and *chain-based* approaches.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The additional vulnerabilities of PoS schemes are directly related to their advantage: a relatively low amount of calculations required when constructing a blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The low amount of computing power involved allows a class of attacks that replace a non-negligible portion of the main blockchain with a hijacked version.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] These attacks are called in literature by different names, including *Long-Range*, *Alternative History*, *Alternate History*, and *History Revision*, and are unfeasible in the PoW schemes due to the sheer volume of calculations required.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The early stages of a blockchain are much more malleable for rewriting, as they likely have much smaller group of stakeholders involved, simplifying the collusion.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] If the per-block and per-transaction rewards are offered, then the malicious group can, for example, redo the entire history and collect these rewards.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The classic "Short-Range" attack (bribery attack) that rewrites just a small tail portion of the chain is also possible.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The PoS schemes enable low-cost creation of blockchain alternatives starting at any point in history (*costless simulation*); submitting these forks to eager validators endangers the stability of the system.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] If this situation persists, it can allow double-spending, where a digital token can be spent more than once.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] This can be mitigated through penalizing validators who validate conflicting chains ("economic finality") or by structuring the rewards so that there is no economic incentive to create conflicts.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Byzantine-fault-tolerance-based PoS are generally considered robust against this threat (see below).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The smaller amount of calculations required for solving the puzzle for high-value stakeholders helps to avoid excessive hardware.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Also known as "committee-based", this scheme involves an election of a committee of validators using a verifiable random function with probabilities of being elected higher with higher stake.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Validators then randomly take turns producing blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] NPoS is utilized by Ouroboros Praos and BABE.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The BFT consensus is used to finalize the most-voted block.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The scheme works as long as no more than a third of validators are dishonest.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] BFT schemes are used in Tendermint and Casper FFG.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Proof of stake delegated systems use a two-stage process: first, the stakeholders elect a validation committee, a.k.a.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] *witnesses*, by voting proportionally to their stakes, then the witnesses take turns in a round-robin fashion to propose new blocks that are then voted upon by the witnesses, usually in the BFT-like fashion.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Since there are fewer validators in the DPoS than in many other PoS schemes, the consensus can be established faster.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The scheme is used in many chains, including EOS, Lisk, Tron.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] In the liquid PoS anyone with a stake can declare themselves a validator, but for the small holders it makes sense to delegate their voting rights instead to larger players in exchange for some benefits (like periodic payouts).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] A market is established where the validators compete on the fees, reputation, and other factors.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Token holders are free to switch their support to another validator at any time.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The exact definition of "stake" varies from implementation to implementation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] For instance, some cryptocurrencies use the concept of "coin age", the product of the number of tokens with the amount of time that a single user has held them, rather than merely the number of tokens, to define a validator's stake.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The first functioning implementation of a proof-of-stake cryptocurrency was Peercoin, introduced in 2012.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Other cryptocurrencies, such as Blackcoin, Nxt, Cardano, and Algorand followed.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] However, as of 2017, PoS cryptocurrencies were still not as widely used as proof-of-work cryptocurrencies.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] In September 2022, Ethereum, the second-largest cryptocurrency, switched from PoW to a PoS consensus mechanism, after several proposals and some delays.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] US regulators have argued over the legal status of the proof-of-stake model, with the Securities and Exchange Commission claiming that staking rewards are the equivalent of interest, so coins such as ether and ada are financial securities.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] However, in 2024, the SEC sidestepped the question by recognising Ethereum market funds on condition that they did not stake their coins.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] The level of staking of ether at 27% of total supply was low compared with Cardano (66%) and Solana (63%).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] However, not staking their tokens meant that the funds were losing about 3% of potential returns a year.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] In January 2022, Erik Thedéen, the vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority, called on the EU to ban the PoW model in favor of PoS because of the latter's lower energy consumption.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-stake] Ethereum's switch to proof-of-stake was estimated to have cut its energy use by over 99%.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Proof of work was later popularized by Bitcoin as a foundation for consensus in a permissionless decentralized network, in which miners compete to append blocks and mine new currency, each miner experiencing a success probability proportional to the computational effort expended.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] PoW and PoS (proof of stake) remain the two best known Sybil deterrence mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In the context of cryptocurrencies they are the most common mechanisms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] A key feature of proof-of-work schemes is their asymmetry: the *work* – the computation – must be moderately hard (yet feasible) on the prover or requester side but easy to check for the verifier or service provider.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This idea is also known as a CPU cost function, client puzzle, computational puzzle, or CPU pricing function.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Another common feature is built-in incentive-structures that reward allocating computational capacity to the network with value in the form of cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The purpose of proof-of-work algorithms is not proving that certain work was carried out or that a computational puzzle was "solved", but deterring manipulation of data by establishing large energy and hardware-control requirements to be able to do so.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems have been criticized by some environmentalists who argue that it generates externalities that are not reflected in market electricity prices which do not compensate for the economic and social benefits.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The interruptible load characteristics of proof-of-work mining provide demand-response services and support the integration of variable renewable energy under certain market and grid conditions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The concept of Proof of Work (PoW) has its roots in early research on combating spam and preventing denial-of-service attacks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] One of the earliest implementations of PoW was Hashcash, created by British cryptographer Adam Back in 1997.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] It was designed as an anti-spam mechanism that required email senders to perform a small computational task, effectively proving that they expended resources (in the form of CPU time) before sending an email.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This task was trivial for legitimate users but would impose a significant cost on spammers attempting to send bulk messages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Hashcash's system was based on the concept of finding a hash value that met certain criteria, a task that required computational effort and thus served as a "proof of work." The idea was that by making it computationally expensive to send large volumes of email, spamming would be reduced.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] One popular system, used in Hashcash, uses partial hash inversions to prove that computation was done, as a goodwill token to send an e-mail.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Whether PoW systems can actually solve a particular denial-of-service issue such as the spam problem is subject to debate; the system must make sending spam emails obtrusively unproductive for the spammer, but should also not prevent legitimate users from sending their messages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In other words, a genuine user should not encounter any difficulties when sending an email, but an email spammer would have to expend a considerable amount of computing power to send out many emails at once.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Proof-of-work systems are being used by other, more complex cryptographic systems such as Bitcoin, which uses a system similar to Hashcash.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Proof of work traces its theoretical origins to early efforts to combat digital abuse, evolving significantly over time to address security, accessibility, and broader applications beyond its initial anti-spam purpose.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The idea first emerged in 1993 as a deterrent for junk mail, but it was Satoshi Nakamoto’s 2008 whitepaper, "Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic Cash System," that solidified proof of work's potential as a cornerstone of blockchain networks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This development reflects the rising demands for secure, trustless systems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The earliest appearance of proof of work was in 1993, when Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor proposed a system to curb junk email by requiring senders to perform computationally demanding tasks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In their paper, "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail," they outlined methods such as computing modular square roots, designed to be challenging to solve yet straightforward to verify, establishing a foundational principle of proof of work's asymmetry.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This asymmetry is crucial to the effectiveness of proof of work, ensuring that tasks like sending spam are costly for attackers, while verification remains efficient for legitimate users.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This conceptual groundwork found practical use in 1997 with Adam Back’s Hashcash, a system that required senders to compute a partial hash inversion of the SHA-1 algorithm, producing a hash with a set number of leading zeros.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoin, launched in 2009 by Satoshi Nakamoto, marked a pivotal shift by adapting Hashcash's proof of work for cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Nakamoto's Bitcoin whitepaper outlined a system using the SHA-256 algorithm, where miners compete to solve cryptographic puzzles to append blocks to the blockchain, earning rewards in the process.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Unlike Hashcash's static proofs, Bitcoin's proof of work algorithm dynamically adjusts its difficulty based on the average time taken to mine a block in the previous epoch, ensuring a consistent block time of approximately 10 minutes, creating a tamper-proof chain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This innovation transformed proof of work from a standalone deterrent into a consensus mechanism for a decentralized network, emphasizing financial incentives over computational effort.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Initially mined with standard CPUs, Bitcoin saw a rapid transition to GPUs, then to FPGAs and finally to ASICs, which vastly outperformed general hardware in solving SHA-256 puzzles.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] To address Bitcoin's increasing reliance on specialized hardware, Litecoin changed the Hashcash hash function from SHA-256 to Scrypt.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Developed by Colin Percival and detailed in the technical specification "The scrypt Password-Based Key Derivation Function," Scrypt was designed as a memory-intensive algorithm, requiring a moderate amount of RAM to compute.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Litecoin's goal of making mining more accessible to users with general-purpose hardware didn't last long, as mining followed a similar migration from CPUs through GPUs and FPGAs to ASICs.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] There are two classes of proof-of-work protocols.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Known-solution protocols tend to have slightly lower variance than unbounded probabilistic protocols because the variance of a rectangular distribution is lower than the variance of a Poisson distribution (with the same mean).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] A generic technique for reducing variance is to use multiple independent sub-challenges, as the average of multiple samples will have a lower variance.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] There are also fixed-cost functions such as the time-lock puzzle.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Finally, some PoW systems offer **shortcut** computations that allow participants who know a secret, typically a private key, to generate cheap PoWs.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The rationale is that mailing-list holders may generate stamps for every recipient without incurring a high cost.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Whether such a feature is desirable depends on the usage scenario.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] At the IACR conference Crypto 2022 researchers presented a paper describing Ofelimos, a blockchain protocol with a consensus mechanism based on "proof of useful work" (PoUW).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Rather than miners consuming energy in solving complex, but essentially useless, puzzles to validate transactions, Ofelimos achieves consensus while simultaneously providing a decentralized optimization problem solver.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The protocol is built around Doubly Parallel Local Search (DPLS), a local search algorithm that is used as the PoUW component.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The paper gives an example that implements a variant of WalkSAT, a local search algorithm to solve Boolean problems.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Optimisable proof of work (OPoW) is a variant of proof of work in which the proof-of-work algorithms themselves can be optimised without causing network instability or centralisation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The mechanism incentivises two categories of participants: miners who compute solutions and are rewarded for adopting the most efficient algorithms, and algorithm contributors who develop and submit improved algorithms and earn rewards based on their adoption by miners.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] By decoupling the solving of computational problems from block creation, OPoW allows many solutions to be found per block, effectively creating a synthetic market for algorithms.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In 2009, the Bitcoin network went online.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoin is a proof-of-work digital currency that, like Finney's RPoW, is also based on the Hashcash PoW.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] But in Bitcoin, double-spend protection is provided by a decentralized P2P protocol for tracking transfers of coins, rather than the hardware trusted computing function used by RPoW.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has better trustworthiness because it is protected by computation.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoins are "mined" using the Hashcash proof-of-work function by individual miners and verified by the decentralized nodes in the P2P Bitcoin network.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Since the creation of Bitcoin, proof-of-work has been the predominant design of peer-to-peer cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Studies have estimated the total energy consumption of cryptocurrency mining.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The PoW mechanism requires a vast amount of computing resources, which consume a significant amount of electricity.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] 2018 estimates from the University of Cambridge equate Bitcoin's energy consumption to that of Switzerland.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Each block that is added to the blockchain, starting with the block containing a given transaction, is called a confirmation of that transaction.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Ideally, merchants and services that receive payment in the cryptocurrency should wait for at least one confirmation to be distributed over the network, before assuming that the payment was done.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The more confirmations that the merchant waits for, the more difficult it is for an attacker to successfully reverse the transaction in a blockchain—unless the attacker controls more than half the total network power, in which case it is called a 51% attack.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Within the Bitcoin community there are groups working together in mining pools.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Some miners use application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) for PoW.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This trend toward mining pools and specialized ASICs has made mining some cryptocurrencies economically infeasible for most players without access to the latest ASICs, nearby sources of inexpensive energy, or other special advantages.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Some PoWs claim to be ASIC-resistant, i.e. to limit the efficiency gain that an ASIC can have over commodity hardware, like a GPU, to be well under an order of magnitude.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] ASIC resistance has the advantage of keeping mining economically feasible on commodity hardware, but also contributes to the corresponding risk that an attacker can briefly rent access to a large amount of unspecialized commodity processing power to launch a 51% attack against a cryptocurrency.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] By design, Bitcoin's Proof of Work consensus algorithm is vulnerable to Majority Attacks (51% attacks).
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Any miner with over 51% of mining power is able to control the canonical chain until their hash power falls below 50%.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] This allows them to reorg the blockchain, double-spend, censor transactions, and completely control block production.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] There was a notable double-spend on Bitcoin in March 2013 when the chain split due to a bug in the Bitcoin 0.8.0 client.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] While on the 0.8.0 chain, a merchant (OKPAY) confirmed a $10k deposit from a customer.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoin miners then 51% attacked the network, reverting 24 blocks and reversing the transaction leading to the customer's deposit.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The customer then double-spent the bitcoin on the canonical pre-0.8.0 chain as an experiment.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] A 2025 paper by Duke University Finance Professor Campbell Harvey estimates that a week-long 51% attack on Bitcoin could be executed with only $6 Billion at Oct 2025 prices.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The total cost of attack would be less than 1% of Bitcoin's total value.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] An attacker could profit from shorting Bitcoin or for non-economic reasons.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Bitcoin has asymmetric security where Bitcoin miners control its security, but they aren't the same people who hold Bitcoin.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Unlike with Proof of Stake, there is much weaker economic incentive for those who control security to protect the network under Proof of Work.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Historically, many Proof of Work networks with low security budgets have fallen under 51% attacks., which highlights PoW's asymmetric security.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The amount of protection provided by PoW mining is close to the security budget of the network, which is roughly equal to the total block reward.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] With each additional halving, Bitcoin's security budget continues to fall relative to its market cap.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In the past, Bitcoin developers were hopeful that transaction fees would rise to replace the declining block subsidy, but this has not been the case as transaction fees still only generate 1% of the total block reward.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] There are concerns that Bitcoin's security is unsustainable in the long run due to the declining security budget caused by its halvings.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Miners compete to solve crypto challenges on the bitcoin blockchain, and their solutions must be agreed upon by all nodes and reach consensus.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The solutions are then used to validate transactions, add blocks and generate new bitcoins.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Miners are rewarded for solving these puzzles and successfully adding new blocks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] However, the Bitcoin-style mining process is very energy intensive because the proof of work is shaped like a lottery mechanism.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The underlying computational work has no other use but to provide security to the network that provides open access and has to work in adversarial conditions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Miners have to use a lot of energy to add a new block containing a transaction to the blockchain.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] The energy used in this competition is what fundamentally gives Bitcoin its level of security and resistance to attacks.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Also, miners have to invest computer hardwares that need large spaces as fixed cost.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In January 2022 vice-chair of the European Securities and Markets Authority Erik Thedéen called on the EU to ban the proof of work model in favor of the proof of stake model due its lower energy emissions.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] In November 2022 the state of New York enacted a two-year moratorium on cryptocurrency mining that does not completely use renewable energy as a power source for two years.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] Existing mining companies will be grandfathered in to continue mining without the use of renewable energy but they will not be allowed to expand or renew permits with the state.
[src:blockchain-consensus/proof-of-work] No new mining companies that do not completely use renewable energy will be allowed to begin mining.
